{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa9194df-9105-44be-91a3-7a7d14c9f43c","content":"Here's my analysis of the evaluation performance issues in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n## 3 Anti-Patterns Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions during evaluation is **expensive**. Evaluation runs frequently (IDE, restore, build), and file I/O blocks the evaluation thread. Move this logic to a target that runs at build time instead.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree**. If large directories exist (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`, artifacts), this becomes very slow. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or subdirectories, or add large directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. While 3 levels is moderate, this pattern compounds in larger repos. Consider flattening the chain or consolidating properties into fewer files.\n\n---\n\n**Most impactful fix:** Replace the `File::ReadAllText` call with a target-based approach, and constrain the glob pattern to specific file types.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ecae2bc0-7ffa-4fd1-b03d-f1fae347a29b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a full picture of this project. Let me analyze it for evaluation performance issues.\n\nThe project has several evaluation performance anti-patterns:\n\n1. **File I/O property function during evaluation** (line 13 in .csproj): `$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))` - This reads a file during evaluation, which is expensive.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern** (line 9): `**\\*.*` - This walks the entire directory tree, which can be very expensive if there are large directories (like node_modules, .git, etc.). The exclude pattern only omits bin/obj but not other potentially large directories.\n\n\n3. **Deep import chain**: The project imports `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` - a 3-level deep import chain. While 3 levels isn't extremely deep, it demonstrates the pattern that can become problematic at scale.","outputTokens":599,"requestId":"1901:287A16:14B9C15:175241F:6A0675C6"},"id":"82286cab-a300-4049-803b-628c88f90d6f","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:24:36.233Z","parentId":"0a015c76-6244-4fef-b8f9-09da6a602537"}
